## 2. Test strategy

### 2.1 Positive tests (happy path)
Verify that the system does what it should when given valid inputs and expected user behaviour.

### 2.2 Negative tests (required for every feature)
Verify robustness against invalid, unexpected, or adversarial inputs.

Mandatory negative test categories per feature:
| Category | Examples |
|---|---|
| Invalid input | null, empty string, wrong type, out-of-range value |
| Missing required fields | submit form with required field absent |
| Malformed requests | invalid JSON, wrong content-type, oversized payload |
| Unexpected action sequence | submit before loading, double-submit, skip required step |
| Boundary values | max length + 1, min value - 1, max count exceeded |

### 2.3 Permission / security tests
| Test | Expected result |
|---|---|
| Unauthenticated request to protected endpoint | 401 / redirect to login |
| Authenticated request with insufficient role | 403 Forbidden |
| User A accessing User B's data | 403 or 404 (no data leak) |
| SQL injection in input fields | Input rejected / sanitised |
| XSS payload in text input | Payload escaped, not executed |

### 2.4 Edge-case tests
- Empty collections (lists, search results, etc.)
- Single-item collections
- Maximum allowed values (string length, array size, numeric range)
- Concurrent duplicate requests (race conditions)
- Session expiry mid-flow

### 2.5 Stress / performance tests
| Scenario | Baseline | Breaking point | Expected degradation |
|---|---|---|---|
| Normal load | __ req/sec | __ req/sec | __ |
| Peak load (10× normal) | | | |
| Sustained load (60 min) | | | |
| Database connection pool exhaustion | | | |

